SIMPLE: motif
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Motif
<hw>Mo"tif</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety>
<def>Motive.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In literature and the fine arts, a salient feature
or element of a composition or work; esp., the theme, or central or
dominant feature;</def> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Music)</fld>,
<def>a motive{3}. See also <er>leitmotif</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>motif</qex>, of old things lost, is a favorite one for
the serious ballade.</q> <rj><qau>R. M. Alden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The design . . . is . . . based on the peacock -- a
<qex>motif</qex> favored by decorative artists of all ages.</q>
<rj><qau>R. D. Benn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Dressmaking)</fld> <def>A decorative
appliqu⟦eacute⟧ design or figure, as of lace or velvet, used in
trimming; also, a repeated design.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motific</ent>⟦br⟧
